There is an infallible way to determine proper usage.  Simply try them
one at a time.  Items in a list must be consistent in case.  You would
never say 'George is going to the store with I', so you shouldn't say
&quot;George is going to the store with Fred and I.&quot;  The word 'with' in this
sentence makes 'Fred' and 'I' the OBJECTS of the preposition, and thus
the objective case 'me' is the proper form.  English is not particularly
'case intensive', since there are really only two cases, and only
pronouns are affected, unlike Latin that has 6 cases!
